## Thread.Abort Migration → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — it spawns a thread, waits for a deadline, then forcibly aborts. It also uses `ThreadAbortException` + `ResetAbort` as control flow. All three APIs (`Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`) throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) in .NET 6+.

---

### Why It Breaks

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` injects `ThreadAbortException` into the target thread | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — **no forcible thread termination exists** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` cancels the pending abort | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` fires on abort | Never fires — the exception is never thrown |

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),
            timeout);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout cancellation
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException
                                             && cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes

| Before (Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Uses the thread pool; no manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Timer-based cancellation fires automatically |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timer) | Cooperative — work must check the token |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed; cancellation is cooperative |

---

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfall: Cooperative Cancellation

The **fundamental difference**: `Thread.Abort` forcibly stopped uncooperative code. `CancellationToken` **only works if the code checks it**. The overload accepting `Func<T>` (no token) will still run to completion after timeout — the `TimeoutException` is thrown to the caller, but the work keeps running on the thread pool.

To get true cancellation, callers must use the token-aware overload:

```csharp
// ❌ Work ignores cancellation — keeps running in background after timeout
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => SlowWork(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ Work cooperates — stops promptly
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

---

### Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers if not disposed | Always wrap in `using` (done above) |
| `Thread.Sleep` inside work ignores the token | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |
| Blocking I/O (`socket.Read`) can't be cancelled | Use async overloads that accept `CancellationToken` |
| Truly uncooperative third-party code | Move to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — this is the only .NET 8 equivalent of forcible termination |
